This paper is about Dialogue Act classification, which is a subfield of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and falls under the Computer Science category. The paper proposes a new method for Dialogue Act classification using a context-aware self-attention mechanism coupled with a hierarchical recurrent neural network. This method involves deep learning techniques and is related to several sub-categories of Computer Science. 

cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category as it specifically deals with NLP tasks such as Dialogue Act classification. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also likely as the paper proposes a new method that involves deep learning techniques. 

cs.LG (Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper involves training a neural network to classify Dialogue Acts. 

cs.SD (Sound) is a less likely sub-category, but it is still possible as the paper uses the Switchboard Dialogue Act (SwDA) Corpus, which is a dataset of spoken conversations. 

cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also a less likely sub-category, but it is still possible as Dialogue Act classification can be used to improve information retrieval systems.
